programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. Milly Bradshaw lived with her two children in the Brisbane valley of Brookfield for six years before she met Andrew Wilson. In time, the place became the base for their blended family and was perfect for their shared dream of running a small farm. They started buying cattle, but with their run-down weatherboard cottage well past its use-by date, it was clear they needed a new dwelling: a modern farmhouse. The brief to their architect was simple: a unique home making the best of its location, and as different as possible from the traditional ranch style. Their architect delivered a design that's telescopic, angular and modern in shape, rising from one storey to three and culminating in a two-storey glazed portal framing the master bedroom. Projecting out of the landscape and clad in natural materials such as spotted gum boards, it's a contemporary take on rural living. Andrew, who has plumbing skills, sets out with right-hand man Hamish, an accomplished carpenter, to bring this dynamic form to life. But Milly is busy working so won't be there for the key decisions. The project's scope is breath-taking and even the architect admits it's no easy build. It's supposed to be the next step in their lives together, but as Andrew gets swamped in a quagmire of decision making, it might have the opposite effect

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. Dean and Sherrill Lamb yearn for a simpler existence for themselves and their three children. They've already sold their fruit shops and are planning to sell their house in the pursuit of total self-sufficiency. Designing a new four-pavilion structure themselves, they plan to minimise their carbon footprint while constructing it at Pipers Creek, north of Melbourne. Interested in natural building options, they've settled on one with excellent environmental properties and perfect credentials for Australian conditions: a house made of straw. Their straw bale walls are to be complemented by rammed earth flooring, with every element utilising natural alternatives wherever possible, recycled windows and doors, and a mini-wind turbine to provide power. To help bring it in on budget, Dean and Sherrill will be doing all this themselves, and Dean plans to run straw bale house building classes too. It could provide the perfect balance, helping them to tread gently on the planet while living a more sustainable existence, but although it's a well-intentioned goal, it may not be realistic. Focus soon turns to merely keeping their dream afloat. When you lack experience, manpower and money, the inevitable response is to compromise. The question is, by how much?

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. Before Matt McLelland's wife Anne died six years ago, they'd been looking for a rural property to build on - a place to call home for them and for their four adult children to visit. So when Matt stumbled across 40 acres in central Victoria with spectacular views to Mount Alexander's granite hillside, he knew he'd found the spot. Crucial to the design was accommodating Anne's wish to create a pavilion-style home inspired by the aesthetic of the rural Australian shearing shed. That means featuring the most important element intrinsic to the style - the portal frame. Matt envisions a timber frame clad in corrugated iron - his very own interpretation of the Aussie shed. But this is land studded with granite and no one is quite sure what's beneath the surface, though 70-year-old Matt reckons it's a job he can manage with a bit of help from his builder nephew Mike. But Mike is used to fast-paced city construction sites, not Matt's laid-back, no-frills approach - and when Matt's cronies arrive to help in times of crisis, the collective inexperience makes for a worksite like no other. Last in the series(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. Milly Bradshaw lived with her two children in the Brisbane valley of Brookfield for six years before she met Andrew Wilson. In time, the place became the base for their blended family and was perfect for their shared dream of running a small farm. They started buying cattle, but with their run-down weatherboard cottage well past its use-by date, it was clear they needed a new dwelling: a modern farmhouse. The brief to their architect was simple: a unique home making the best of its location, and as different as possible from the traditional ranch style. Their architect delivered a design that's telescopic, angular and modern in shape, rising from one storey to three and culminating in a two-storey glazed portal framing the master bedroom. Projecting out of the landscape and clad in natural materials such as spotted gum boards, it's a contemporary take on rural living. Andrew, who has plumbing skills, sets out with right-hand man Hamish, an accomplished carpenter, to bring this dynamic form to life. But Milly is busy working so won't be there for the key decisions. The project's scope is breath-taking and even the architect admits it's no easy build. It's supposed to be the next step in their lives together, but as Andrew gets swamped in a quagmire of decision making, it might have the opposite effect

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. Before Matt McLelland's wife Anne died six years ago, they'd been looking for a rural property to build on - a place to call home for them and for their four adult children to visit. So when Matt stumbled across 40 acres in central Victoria with spectacular views to Mount Alexander's granite hillside, he knew he'd found the spot. Crucial to the design was accommodating Anne's wish to create a pavilion-style home inspired by the aesthetic of the rural Australian shearing shed. That means featuring the most important element intrinsic to the style - the portal frame. Matt envisions a timber frame clad in corrugated iron - his very own interpretation of the Aussie shed. But this is land studded with granite and no one is quite sure what's beneath the surface, though 70-year-old Matt reckons it's a job he can manage with a bit of help from his builder nephew Mike. But Mike is used to fast-paced city construction sites, not Matt's laid-back, no-frills approach - and when Matt's cronies arrive to help in times of crisis, the collective inexperience makes for a worksite like no other. Last in the series(n)
